data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0, "Expected at least one user");
    // or: CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty() if using MSTest v3+

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | Add a message, or `CollectionAssert` methods |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` — gives "expected 3 but got 5" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |

**Why it matters:** `Assert.IsTrue` only reports `"Expected: True, Actual: False"` on failure. The specific assertions give meaningful diagnostics (e.g., `"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"`).

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)`
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
